<p class="mgSubItemTitleTxt">Minutes:</p>
<div class="mgWordPara"><div class="WordSection1">
<p class="MsoNormal" style=""><span style=
"border:none windowtext 1.0pt; padding:0cm">The Chair introduced
the item and stated that developer contributions helped the Council
to<span style="">&nbsp;</span> deliver the infrastructure and
services communities needed to support the developments being built
in their communities. This meeting would give the Committee an
opportunity to assess how well the Council was performing in terms
of distributing those developer contributions.</span></p>
<p class="MsoNormal" style="font-weight: bold"><span style=
"border:none windowtext 1.0pt; padding:0cm">&nbsp;</span></p>
<p class="MsoNormal" style=""><span style=
"border:none windowtext 1.0pt; padding:0cm">Deputy Leader (Housing,
Investment and New Homes), Councillor Danny Adilypour, introduced
the report and noted that:</span></p>
<p class="MsoNormal" style="font-weight: bold"><span style=
"border:none windowtext 1.0pt; padding:0cm">&nbsp;</span></p>
<ul style="margin-top:0cm">
<li class="MsoNormal" style="text-align:left"><span style="">The
report provided a comprehensive overview of the Council&rsquo;s
approach to distributing developer contributions and it also
provided some examples of how the Council was ensuring that the
money was spent to benefit communities across the
borough.</span></li>
<li class="MsoNormal" style="text-align:left"><span style="">He
noted that there were three main ways in how the Council obtained
developer contributions - Community Infrastructure Levy (CIL),
Neighbourhood CIL (NCIL) and Section 106 planning obligations
(S106). The Committee heard how the report outlined what the
Council was doing to improve and highlight transparency, improve
delivery of the projects and what it was also doing to ensure that
the distribution of developer contributions aligned with the
Council&rsquo;s</span> <span style="">Growth Plan, Lambeth Local
Plan, Infrastructure Delivery Plan and Borough Plan.</span></li>
<li class="MsoNormal" style="text-align:left"><span style="">The
report also provided an overview of development contributions
received by the Council as of December 2025, along with projections
of what this is likely to look like in the years ahead, although
with the caveat that this was subject to change due to broader
economic conditions, variations in development activity, and
potential changes in national policy or legislation.</span></li>
<li class="MsoNormal" style="text-align:left"><span style=
"">Officers provided additional information as requested by
Committee Members and he welcomed any comments or recommendations
which helped the Council to build on the work it was already
delivering in this policy area.</span></li>
</ul>
<p class="MsoNormal" style="text-align:left"><span style=
"border:none windowtext 1.0pt; padding:0cm">&nbsp;</span></p>
<p class="MsoNormal" style=""><span style="">The Chair invited
witnesses to speak on the agenda item.</span></p>
<p class="MsoNormal" style=""><span style=
"border:none windowtext 1.0pt; padding:0cm">&nbsp;</span></p>
<p class="MsoNormal" style="text-align:left"><span style="">Tayo
Adesina, Trash <span class="SpellE">Gxng</span><span style="">,
informed the Committee that:</span></span></p>
<p class="MsoNormal" style="text-align:left"><span style=
"">&nbsp;</span></p>
<ul style="margin-top:0cm">
<li class="MsoNormal" style=""><span style="">He was a director for
Trash <span class="SpellE">Gxng</span> which was a grassroots
social mobility organisation, ultimately equipping young people
from the ages 11-25 with the creative and employability skills they
required. Trash <span class="SpellE">Gxng</span> focused on
supporting those who are marginalised in the community and often
those who may be economically disadvantaged or facing multiple
barriers, with Special Educational and Disabilities (SEND) and
mental health needs as examples.</span></li>
<li class="MsoNormal" style=""><span style="">Trash <span class=
"SpellE">Gxng</span> received Neighbourhood Community
Infrastructure Levy (NCIL) <span class="GramE">funding</span> and
they were able to demonstrate their impact on the young people it
supported via the fact that 99% participants were strongly enjoying
and engaged in the sessions provided and 90%+ of young people
reported that they had increased self-belief and empowerment to
make better decisions for themselves. He also noted that Trash
<span class="SpellE">Gxng</span> were also able to launch
programmes through the support of this funding and the aid of the
<span class="GramE">Council&rsquo;s<span style="">&nbsp;</span>
&lsquo;</span>Lambeth Made&rsquo; programme.</span></li>
<li class="MsoNormal" style=""><span style="">It would be
beneficial for organisations like Trash <span class=
"SpellE">Gxng</span> if their funding was more stabilised because
if it lost its NCIL backing there was no guarantee that the Council
were able to replace that funding. He added that it would be
disappointing to stop operating when it could evidence over many
years &nbsp;...&nbsp; <a href="mgAi.aspx?ID=67072" title=
"Link to view the full item text for item 4., Developer Contributions">
view the full minutes text for item 4.</a></span></li>
</ul>
</div>
</div> 
					
